<font color="#FF0000">RETURNING VETS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 12 16:15:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
All right, I admit frustration, but I will not admit defeat as of yet!<br><br>
I have been trying to figure things out that have occurred while in ‘Nam and afterwards.  I went in the service in 1967, went to ‘Nam in Nov. of ‘67 and returned Feb. of 1970. Somewhere in between, a lot had happened and a lot that I missed out on.  I understand  and accept this.  There were very few newspapers or radios or television sets where I was. The world moves on.  I came home and the world was vastly different or so it seemed.  Again, to be expected.  What I didn't expect was the open hostility, contemptuous attitudes and the physical and verbal abuse that was not uncommon.  I did not count on that I had to hide or deny the fact that I was a Vietnam veteran just to survive.  And over the span of many years AFTER the US pullout of Vietnam and AFTER the Fall of Saigon.<br><br>
These are my assertions:<br>
1.  That, not only did the returning vets suffer the abuse from a faction within the protest community (I was not the object of abuse in this case that I am aware of), but from the general community as well (this I did suffer).<br>
2.  These abuses were common place, not just isolated instances.<br>
3.  That these abuses extended beyond the war years.<br><br>
I have felt that, by getting to know and understand those within the protest community, I would find some answers.  I have been told that I am &quot;piercingly analytical&quot; and it was meant as a compliment.  But, I think in this case, it is a curse.  I have gone over all the posts in this and other relevant threads, picked each one apart, and found no answers or, maybe, I have just missed them.  In any case, enough pussyfooting around.  I will just ask outright.  Maybe this is not the appropriate thread, but.......<br><br>
Why were these abuses directed at the returning vets?  Why were these same vets abused and ignored beyond the war years?  I can, to a certain extent, understand the anger, hostility and frustrations of the protest community, thus the attacks toward vets as symbols of the government, though I believe this to have been wrong.  Why were these things perpetuated by the general population at large? <br><br>
Jeffery Winkler took a stab at these questions.  I would like to here from others.
